Description: Open source software that facilitates tenant organization and offers a digital lease standard for low income housing in NYC.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: There is a lack of access to a verifiable historical record of affordable housing units and accountability from landlords to follow the law.  It is unacceptable that in 2020 the rent history was only available via a paper form. It is unacceptable that HPD does not have access to detailed data of affordable leases. It could be impossible to illegally deregulate a unit if the data was public. This information asymmetry largely contributes to tenant harassment. Tenants must go through complex administrative processes to get an answer.  Therefore tenants feel pressured to leave their apartments due to ongoing harassment and because they are unaware of their rights and how to fight back.  There are old and new challenges because of Covid that have made on the ground organizing difficult for local organizers and we offer some additional digital resources for better communication with tenants.  If not put on check, Landlord will continue to sidestep the housing laws and continue to raise rents and contribute to the gentrification and defunding of poor and vulnerable communities.   LOTB is designed to be the tool of systemic change on how the community deals with the lack of information about affordable housing. As of November 2020, LOTB suspended its activities

Headquarters Regions: Greater Philadelphia Area, East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: If you’re a Delaware resident and want to help change the future of art and design, you should consider the Delaware College of Art and Design in Wilmington, Delaware. The school was founded through a creative partnership between Pratt Institute and the Corcoran College of Art and Design. Its goal is to educate talented and dedicated young artists to become art makers, problem solvers and visual communicators of the highest caliber who can provide a fresh perspective of the world. The academics offered at the college include a comprehensive associate’s of fine arts degree that focuses on studio education in art and design balanced with liberal arts classes so that students develop the skills, concepts and values in their particular area of study. Students have access to state-of-the-art facilities as they pursue their degree, from technologically advanced computer imaging and graphics labs to full darkrooms to upscale painting, drawing and design studios. Other resources available include the Toni and Stuart B. Young Gallery, Edgar A. Thronson Library, the Saville housing facilities and Tatiana Copeland Student Center, which features game rooms, lounge areas and study nooks for students in their free time. Merit-based scholarships are available to students who apply by March 15 and demonstrate exceptional academic achievement and potential. Other forms of financial aid include federal and state programs, as well as student loans. The admissions process requires students to complete an application and submit an official high school transcript and artistic portfolio.
